# Simulations & Modeling

Simulations operationalize the theoretical models and empirical estimates described in the
papers (see `notes/papers/`) using real or synthetic data.

## Grounding
- Tie every simulation to a specific source: link the relevant `notes/papers/<slug>.md` and/or
  concept note at the top of the script.
- Document the **model**, its **assumptions**, and all **parameters** (with values and where they
  come from) in a header docstring or top markdown cell.

## Bayesian work (PyMC)
- State **priors explicitly** and justify them (informative vs weakly-informative, and why).
- Set random seeds for reproducibility.
- Report **convergence diagnostics** (trace plots, R-hat, divergences, effective sample size),
  not just point estimates.
- Communicate results as **distributions / credible intervals**, conveying uncertainty.

## General
- Keep models small, modular, and documented; factor shared logic into `src/`.
- Make runs reproducible (seed, pinned params) and runnable top-to-bottom.
- Where possible, **validate** against the source paper's reported results and note any divergence.
- Type-hint functions; run `ruff` and `mypy` on code in `src/`.
